@node "tooltypes" "AHelp Tooltypes"
@{b}Tooltypes@{ub}

  The following tooltypes are accepted and initialized by AHelp:

  CX_POPUP      Set this tooltype to YES and AHelp will popup at its start.
                This option is not recommended if AHelp shall run slightly in
                the background.

  CX_POPKEY     Set a key-definition in this tooltype. If this/these key(s)
                is/are pressed, AHelp will popup if it`s iconified.

  CX_ICONKEY    Same as popkey, but AHelp will iconify it`s window then instead
                of popping it up.
   
  CX_CLOSE      Set this tooltype to YES and AHelp will exit if you press the
                window`s close gadget. If you set it to no or do not set it at
                all AHelp will iconify when the close gadget is pressed.

  APPICON       Set this tooltype to YES if AHelp shall display an appicon when
                it`s iconified.

  HELPPATH      Set your help-path in this tooltype.

  VIEWERGUIDE   If you don`t want to use amigaguide.library for viewing guide
                files specify here your favourite guide viewer. Use the variable
                %f for the filename. 

  VIEWEROTHER   Same as VIEWERGUIDE but this is for all non-guide files.



  Examples:

  CX_POPUP   = YES
  CX_ICONKEY = HELP
  CX_CLOSE   = NO
  APPICON    = YES
  HELPPATH   = HELP:
  VIEWERGUIDE=Sys:Utilities/PowerGuide %f
  (VIEWEROTHER=MuchMore %f)

  Tooltypes in brackets are inactive.
 
@endnode

@node "install" "Installation"
@{b}Installation@{ub}

  To install AHelp simply doubleclick the "Install" script.
  Please do not install AHelp by hand because the Installer will
  create a configuration file for you which should be present.

  If there any problems, please contact @{"me" link "autor"}.

@endnode

@node "wasmacht" "Introduction"
@{b}Introduction@{ub}

  Let`s have a short visit to the past...

  ...Commodore introduced the HELP: assign in 1992 but it seems
  that they forgot to include a program which allows easy access
  to the documents stored in that path...

  And now here`s AHelp. This program does this job as good as
  possible. AHelp runs as a commodity fully in the background.
  Simply press HELP (or an other HotKey defined by you) and a nice
  GUI appears. You can select now between all documents stored
  in HELP: (or a drawer of your choice).

  From version 1.2 on AHelp has also some kind of little directory
  browser implemented. You can browse through all the directories
  on your harddisk.
 
  Additionally there are different options you can choose
  in the Prefs Program. Simply have a look at @{"usage" link "ques"}.

@endnode

